The Federal Road Safety Corps (FRSC) has restated its stand on the ban of two passengers occupying the front seat of commercial vehicles across the country. Corps Public Education Officer, Bisi Kazeem disclosed this in an interview on Friday in Abuja. Kazeem said that the FRSC is still in the business of enforcing compliance on all traffic laws, adding that the corps would not relent in ensuring safety at all cost. According to him, the law is very clear on overloading and the corps is sustaining existing efforts to ensure that the law is obeyed by all. “The operational arm of the corps is effecting arrest on daily basis, but one thing you should know is that most of these offenders already know and avoid the areas where our patrol teams operate. “But, we are on top of this like we have been on any other challenge that militates against safety on our roads and I assure you that perpetrators are been arrested at all times,” he said. On the security situation in the country, Kazeem said that the FRSC is prepared to curtail the rising cases of kidnapping considering the wave of kidnapping on the highways in recent time. READ ALSO: FCTA sets up to two quarantine centres for suspected Coronavirus patients He added that the FRSC within the geographical sphere of the country as a paramilitary outfit is aware of the contemporary security situation in the country. “I am happy to inform you that the corps is tactical, highly proactive and will always play its role by providing intelligence to relevant security agencies. “We believe that the collaborative efforts of our combined security apparatus will definitely overcome every form of insecurity that bedevils us in recent times,” Kazeem stated.